Multiple important thermophysical characteristics of the electrolyte solvents studied in this work are not well documented in the literature at the time of writing. Namely, most values for the vapour thermal conductivity coefficient (

                              λ
                              v

                        ), the vapour dynamic viscosity coefficient (

                              μ
                              v

                        ), and the vapour binary diffusion coefficient (

                              D
                              ab

                        ) could not be found in literature within the temperature range of interest, except for IPA [52]. For this reason, semi-empirical equations (see Table 2
                        ) were used to estimate some of these characteristics for most simulated solvents. Characteristics estimated with equations from Table 2 are highlighted in Table 1. This approach yielded good results in previous work [22].

The effects of these parameters on the dispersion rate of vapours are evident in the DMC simulations. From values listed in Table 7
                        , it would be expected that the dispersion rate of DMC-LVP vapours should be dramatically reduced in contrast to those of the DMC-HVP approach. This is due to the DMC-LVP having only 72 % and 34 % of the evaporation flux and inlet concentration of DMC-HVP, respectively. Instead, as shown in Fig. 13, their results are comparable, with DMC-LVP being obviously slower, but with dispersion speeds that are of the same scale to DMC-HVP. In fact, for both DMC simulations, PAC2 values were reached at similar times, with comparable error ranges (see Table 8
                        ). In this case, almost all thermo-physical parameters are the same, except for the binary diffusion coefficient, where the DMC-LVP value is more than twice as the one for the DMC-HVP value. It is then a reasonable assumption that the low evaporation and concentration, which weakens the convection-based dispersion mechanism of the LVP approach, is compensated by its high diffusion coefficient, which boosts the diffusive-based dispersion mechanism.
